  "properties": {
    "encrypted": "false",
    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\n1. Take a look at the `move_or_left()` and `move_or_right()` functions in `custom.py`.\r\n\r\n   * Each function checks if the `Painter` can move forward.\r\n   \r\n   * If it can, it moves forward.\r\n   \r\n   * But if it *can't* move, the program currently does nothing, which means the `Painter` gets stuck!\r\n\r\n2. Add an `else` statement in each function so that:\r\n\r\n   * If the `Painter` *can't* move in `move_or_left()`, it turns left.\r\n   \r\n   * If the `Painter` *can't* move in `move_or_right()`, it turns right.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/b392869ea6d6a41cf49b74005b6cb0ed-choiceD.gif)\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n<i class=\"fa-solid fa-laptop\"></i> **Coding Tip**\r\n\r\nYour `Painter` should always do something during a loop -- either move forward or turn. Use `if/else` to make sure every situation is handled.",
